WEBVTT

00:16.650 --> 00:17.950
Sir?

00:17.952 --> 00:20.486
I, Fitzgerald Thomas Grant III,

00:20.488 --> 00:23.155
do solemnly swear
that I will faithfully execute

00:23.157 --> 00:25.657
the Office of President
of the United States

00:25.659 --> 00:27.960
and will,
to the best of my ability,

00:27.962 --> 00:30.529
preserve, protect,
and defend

00:30.531 --> 00:32.631
the Constitution
of the United States,

00:32.633 --> 00:33.632
so help me, God.

00:33.634 --> 00:35.067
I have to go.

00:44.011 --> 00:44.977
I'm ready.

00:46.547 --> 00:49.248
Well?

00:49.250 --> 00:51.216
I'm done with
the first half.

00:51.218 --> 00:52.017
And?

00:52.019 --> 00:55.154
You can cut Chapter Two.

00:55.156 --> 00:57.689
Chapter Two is important.

00:57.691 --> 00:59.324
Fitz gets shot
in Chapter Two.

00:59.326 --> 01:01.326
I rewrote Chapter Two.

01:01.328 --> 01:04.329
Chapter Two is where I relate
to the American people

01:04.331 --> 01:05.597
through emotion and grief.

01:05.599 --> 01:07.366
The American people don't care
about your bromides

01:07.368 --> 01:08.567
and talking points, Mellie.

01:08.569 --> 01:11.236
What they do care about
is you,

01:11.238 --> 01:14.173
pulling back the mask and
finally offering a real glimpse

01:14.175 --> 01:15.741
inside the deepest,
darkest corners of your soul.

01:15.743 --> 01:18.010
That means you can cut
Chapter Two...
Olivia --

01:18.012 --> 01:20.145
and replace it with the chapter
on why you stayed.

01:23.017 --> 01:24.183
What?

01:29.557 --> 01:32.858
When you discovered that Fitz
had taken up with a mistress,

01:32.860 --> 01:35.694
you pretended not to know
about it and you stayed.

01:35.696 --> 01:36.795
Why?

01:38.966 --> 01:40.466
[ Sighs ]

01:40.468 --> 01:42.634
That chapter is missing,

01:42.636 --> 01:46.371
and that chapter is what the
American people want to read.

01:46.373 --> 01:49.374
It's what<i> I</i> want to read.
It's all anyone wants to read.

01:49.376 --> 01:51.610
Why did you stay?
Why did you lie?

01:51.612 --> 01:53.812
Was it 'cause of ambition,
or was it for love?

01:53.814 --> 01:57.549
What exactly was it about Fitz
or the White House or herself

01:57.551 --> 02:02.121
that made Mellie Grant turn
a blind eye all those years?

02:02.123 --> 02:04.256
What was running through
her head?

02:04.258 --> 02:05.591
Were you having an affair?

02:05.593 --> 02:07.259
Did you have a side piece
of your very own?

02:07.261 --> 02:09.261
Because when Fitz was screwing
another woman,

02:09.263 --> 02:11.163
you didn't seem to care,
and we want to know why.

02:13.834 --> 02:17.269
[ Exhales sharply ]

02:17.271 --> 02:19.471
You really can compartmentalize
like nobody's business.

02:21.942 --> 02:23.675
You asked for Olivia Pope.

02:23.677 --> 02:25.177
You got Olivia Pope.

02:35.789 --> 02:37.656
[ Chewing loudly ]

02:45.833 --> 02:48.167
What year did Senator Grant
graduate Yale?

02:48.169 --> 02:50.335
Huck's on college
and law school. Ask him.

02:50.337 --> 02:51.703
He doesn't answer
my questions.

02:51.705 --> 02:53.372
He either pretends I'm invisible
or growls like a dog.

02:53.374 --> 02:54.806
That's just Huck.
He growls.

02:54.808 --> 02:55.140
That's not comforting.

02:59.046 --> 03:01.446
Hey, what year did Senator Grant
graduate Yale?

03:01.448 --> 03:02.714
How should I know?

03:02.716 --> 03:04.650
We're supposed to be
fact-checking this book, Huck.

03:04.652 --> 03:06.518
I am fact-checking this book,
Marcus.

03:06.520 --> 03:08.287
That's funny.

03:08.289 --> 03:09.454
'Cause it looks a lot like
you're watching a soccer game.

03:09.456 --> 03:11.390
It's called multitasking.

03:11.392 --> 03:14.493
Whatever. Here.

03:14.495 --> 03:16.195
You might want to
double-check your work.

03:17.364 --> 03:18.864
Yes!

03:18.866 --> 03:19.965
Yes.

03:19.967 --> 03:21.967
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

03:21.969 --> 03:23.969
What is this?

03:23.971 --> 03:25.571
Your wake-up call.

03:25.573 --> 03:27.306
"Do you consider
Vice President Ross

03:27.308 --> 03:29.007
a viable Presidential
candidate?"

03:29.009 --> 03:30.509
There's a number
next to it.

03:30.511 --> 03:32.044
93.

03:32.046 --> 03:34.713
93%.

03:34.715 --> 03:37.549
54% of people think you'd be
the immediate front runner

03:37.551 --> 03:39.418
for the Republican nomination,
should you enter the race.

03:39.420 --> 03:41.420
This is a poll.
It's a wake-up call.

03:41.422 --> 03:42.821
Well, this is...

03:42.823 --> 03:44.690
It's...

03:44.692 --> 03:45.824
Wow, 93.

03:45.826 --> 03:48.527
That's...weird.

03:48.529 --> 03:51.196
I already said
I'm not running for President.

03:51.198 --> 03:52.664
44.

03:52.666 --> 03:53.865
I don't want to
talk about --

03:53.867 --> 03:56.101
The number of people
who've held the Oval,

03:56.103 --> 03:58.170
the one office in the world
where you pick up the phone

03:58.172 --> 03:59.905
and 10 minutes later,
a mountain shifts.

03:59.907 --> 04:02.841
That paper says you're one of
the handful of folks on Earth

04:02.843 --> 04:05.277
capable of doing that job.

04:05.279 --> 04:07.346
Did you hear
what I just said, Susan?

04:09.950 --> 04:11.850
If you turn your back
on this,

04:11.852 --> 04:13.719
if you don't even explore
the option,

04:13.721 --> 04:17.322
you will regret it every day
for the rest of your life.

04:19.560 --> 04:21.293
I have a lot to say.

04:21.295 --> 04:23.262
Good.

04:23.264 --> 04:28.367
But I'm gonna take your advice
and try to be more concise.

04:28.369 --> 04:29.268
No.

04:32.039 --> 04:33.905
This is a fantastic
opportunity.

04:33.907 --> 04:36.041
If we change the definition
of the words "fantastic"

04:36.043 --> 04:36.908
<i> and</i> "opportunity."

04:36.910 --> 04:38.744
Lillian Forrester...
Hack.

04:38.746 --> 04:40.712
...is one of the most respected
journalists in the game.

04:40.714 --> 04:42.080
This will be big.

04:42.082 --> 04:43.315
She did that piece on the Pope,
the one you liked.

04:43.317 --> 04:44.249
You said it was good.

04:44.251 --> 04:46.318
It was smart,
for Lillian Forrester.

04:46.320 --> 04:48.086
The Vatican let her
into its bedchamber

04:48.088 --> 04:49.254
and she screwed them
sideways.

04:49.256 --> 04:50.756
She pillaged,
she plundered.

04:50.758 --> 04:51.657
She was fair and balanced.

04:51.659 --> 04:53.058
She's a loaded gun.

04:53.060 --> 04:54.726
She wants to fire at us,
fine.

04:54.728 --> 04:56.561
But to press the barrel of a gun
to our temple?

04:56.563 --> 04:57.763
<i> My</i> temple.

04:57.765 --> 05:00.132
<i> My</i> temple.

05:00.134 --> 05:02.501
Not<i> ours</i> -- mine.

05:04.438 --> 05:06.405
The election is closing in.

05:06.407 --> 05:07.906
We're six months out from Iowa.

05:07.908 --> 05:10.342
Now is the time to set the table
for your successor.

05:10.344 --> 05:13.178
A profile like this?

05:13.180 --> 05:15.947
It's fine --
when you're out of office.

05:15.949 --> 05:18.583
The only thing she wants, the
only thing she's interested in,

05:18.585 --> 05:20.352
is fatally wounding you,
stuffing you,

05:20.354 --> 05:22.754
and mounting your head
above her editor's desk.

05:22.756 --> 05:25.324
Whether you want to accept it or
not, Cyrus, I am on my way out.

05:25.326 --> 05:26.958
Let's let our guard down
a little.

05:26.960 --> 05:28.827
Start shaping our legacy.

05:28.829 --> 05:30.929
Set it up.

05:33.667 --> 05:36.001
None of this has anything to do
with my abilities as President.

05:36.003 --> 05:36.935
You don't think so?

05:36.937 --> 05:38.670
Why I stayed?

05:38.672 --> 05:40.505
I shouldn't be wasting precious
space on that subject.

05:40.507 --> 05:42.641
It's inappropriate.
It's irrelevant.

05:42.643 --> 05:44.142
We need to find an answer,
Mellie,

05:44.144 --> 05:45.310
and we need to put it
in your book,

05:45.312 --> 05:48.280
because if we don't,
people will speculate.

05:48.282 --> 05:50.315
People can speculate
all they want.

05:50.317 --> 05:52.718
You realize this is the question
you will get asked

05:52.720 --> 05:55.454
at every step on your book tour,
every campaign function,

05:55.456 --> 05:57.989
every sit-down with Diane Sawyer
and Barbara Walters.

05:57.991 --> 06:00.225
Trust me, you omit this part
of your book,

06:00.227 --> 06:02.060
it will only lead
to more questions.

06:02.062 --> 06:03.862
This is what
they want to know.

06:03.864 --> 06:05.364
They don't get to know.

06:05.366 --> 06:06.465
It's none of their business.

06:06.467 --> 06:07.999
You can't say that.

06:08.001 --> 06:10.469
I know these are incredibly
difficult questions,

06:10.471 --> 06:12.904
but I wouldn't be helping you
by avoiding them.

06:15.409 --> 06:17.008
You got any actual food
in this place?

06:17.010 --> 06:18.543
And I mean besides cereal.

06:20.981 --> 06:25.150
You don't know, do you?

06:25.152 --> 06:26.985
[ Sighs ]

06:26.987 --> 06:29.187
You don't know
why you stayed.

06:29.189 --> 06:32.524
[ Scoffs ]

06:32.526 --> 06:34.760
Well, do you know why
you left?

06:38.365 --> 06:40.432
I'm just asking,

06:40.434 --> 06:45.036
'cause maybe your answer
will spark something in me.

06:45.038 --> 06:48.240
At the very least,
maybe I can steal it.

06:51.845 --> 06:53.245
I don't need to answer
that question.

06:53.247 --> 06:54.513
I'm not the one
writing a book.

06:54.515 --> 06:55.914
I'm not the one
running for President.

06:55.916 --> 06:57.482
You are.

07:01.188 --> 07:02.354
You don't know, either,
do you?

07:06.059 --> 07:09.094
Tougher than you thought,
right?

07:13.400 --> 07:17.569
[ Breathes deeply ]

07:17.571 --> 07:20.305
What's for lunch?

07:29.650 --> 07:31.450
Ground rules --

07:31.452 --> 07:33.151
if we choose to officially
move forward with this article,

07:33.153 --> 07:34.786
your questions
would need to pertain

07:34.788 --> 07:37.155
to previously
agreed-upon topics only.

07:37.157 --> 07:38.757
Those can be found
on page two.

07:38.759 --> 07:41.226
Lillian, think of these
more as discussion points.

07:41.228 --> 07:43.628
The President's past policies,
his future plans,

07:43.630 --> 07:44.629
and everything in between.

07:44.631 --> 07:47.599
Emphasis, of course,
on the between.

07:47.601 --> 07:48.967
What we're doing
in the present,

07:48.969 --> 07:51.803
we're calling this
our Year of Achievement.

07:51.805 --> 07:55.507
Year of Achievement?
Catchy.

07:55.509 --> 07:57.943
This conversation
is off the record.

07:57.945 --> 08:00.111
I know.
You're noting.
There's no noting.

08:00.113 --> 08:01.346
You don't even have
the job yet.

08:01.348 --> 08:04.249
ABBY: Mr. President.
How's it going in here?

08:04.251 --> 08:06.651
Very well, sir.
This is Lillian Forrester.

08:06.653 --> 08:09.454
Mr. President.
It is such an honor.

08:09.456 --> 08:11.590
Let's hope you feel that way
after these three days.

08:11.592 --> 08:14.926
Sir, we were just going over
some ground rules

08:14.928 --> 08:17.762
for Lillian's article,
should we decide it's a go.

08:17.764 --> 08:20.499
Cy, she spent a week with Putin.
I think Lillian knows the drill.

08:20.501 --> 08:23.168
Mr. President, did you just
compare yourself to Putin?

08:23.170 --> 08:25.637
No.
Mr. President did not.

08:25.639 --> 08:27.305
I should write that down.

08:27.307 --> 08:29.374
Do you know the meaning
of "off the record"?

08:29.376 --> 08:30.976
Of course I do.

08:30.978 --> 08:32.844
Which is why
I'm only joking.

08:32.846 --> 08:34.212
I get it.

08:34.214 --> 08:35.614
It's your court,
your advantage.

08:35.616 --> 08:36.948
You set the rules,
I follow them.

08:36.950 --> 08:40.318
But, frankly, I'm not interested
in a heavily regulated,

08:40.320 --> 08:43.355
closely guarded interview with
the leader of the free world.

08:43.357 --> 08:44.556
Nor is that
what we want to give you.

08:44.558 --> 08:46.858
I want a conversation
with the man.

08:46.860 --> 08:48.894
A meaningful one.

08:48.896 --> 08:50.996
I want to know,
is Fitzgerald Grant

08:50.998 --> 08:52.364
hell-bent
on making a difference

08:52.366 --> 08:54.065
in the final days
of his presidency,

08:54.067 --> 08:55.800
or is he happy
just tending the store?

08:55.802 --> 08:58.303
I want to know
if the man I voted for

08:58.305 --> 09:00.472
thinks he succeeded
or failed.

09:00.474 --> 09:02.974
I have no
ulterior motive here,

09:02.976 --> 09:06.645
aside from wanting to write
a damn good article.

09:06.647 --> 09:09.214
Do you want me to write
a damn good article?

09:11.585 --> 09:12.884
Of course we do.

09:14.821 --> 09:17.255
Nice meeting you, Lillian.

09:17.257 --> 09:18.823
Nice to meet you, as well,
Mr. President.

09:18.825 --> 09:21.059
The pleasure's all mine.

09:36.910 --> 09:40.879
I was devastated...

09:40.881 --> 09:44.950
when I found out Fitz was having
an affair with you.

09:49.423 --> 09:51.289
I fell into
a deep depression,

09:51.291 --> 09:53.758
and the only thing
that got me through it

09:53.760 --> 09:58.530
was thinking that
you were just a phase.

09:58.532 --> 10:03.101
Fitz and I,
we could survive a phase.

10:03.103 --> 10:07.439
[ Scoffs ]

10:07.441 --> 10:10.108
So I stayed.

10:13.647 --> 10:15.880
[ Sighs ]

10:19.252 --> 10:20.885
That's nice, right?

10:20.887 --> 10:22.087
It's a narrative.

10:22.089 --> 10:23.989
That's a good thing.
Absolutely.

10:23.991 --> 10:25.657
Then why does it feel...
Artificial?

10:25.659 --> 10:26.591
[ Sighs ] Trite.

10:26.593 --> 10:28.059
Untrue.

10:28.061 --> 10:30.295
[ Sighs ] My head feels like
it's about to explode.

10:30.297 --> 10:32.430
You're gonna have to
dig deep, Mellie.

10:32.432 --> 10:33.398
Deeper than this.

10:33.400 --> 10:34.733
You say that
like I'm not even trying.

10:34.735 --> 10:36.501
Are you?
Of course I am.

10:36.503 --> 10:37.669
You could have fooled me.

10:37.671 --> 10:39.237
Is that some sort
of reverse-psychology crap

10:39.239 --> 10:40.138
you learned
from your therapist?

10:40.140 --> 10:41.573
I don't have a therapist.

10:41.575 --> 10:44.776
Well, maybe
you should get one.

10:44.778 --> 10:46.511
Why are you...

10:46.513 --> 10:48.813
I'm trying
to help you here.
Please.

10:48.815 --> 10:51.449
Mellie, if you can't tell me
why you chose to st--

10:51.451 --> 10:53.284
I don't have to
tell you anything!

10:53.286 --> 10:54.285
Mellie.

10:54.287 --> 10:56.287
You, of all people.

10:56.289 --> 10:58.790
I don't have to have this
conversation with you.

10:58.792 --> 11:01.793
Answer these questions for you,
explain myself to you!

11:01.795 --> 11:02.961
I'm not asking for my own.

11:02.963 --> 11:05.196
You never had
what we had, Olivia.

11:06.833 --> 11:09.334
23 years.

11:09.336 --> 11:11.302
You may have had
your cheap hotel rooms

11:11.304 --> 11:13.438
and your White House closets
and your secret homes in Vermont

11:13.440 --> 11:15.206
that you didn't think
anybody else knew about.

11:15.208 --> 11:20.979
But as far as actual
real relationships go...

11:20.981 --> 11:23.682
you were just a blip
on his radar.

11:23.684 --> 11:25.350
[ Laughs ]

11:25.352 --> 11:29.487
A plaything he used
to pass his time with

11:29.489 --> 11:31.156
until trash day
rolled around

11:31.158 --> 11:33.224
and you got boxed up
and shipped off --

11:33.226 --> 11:35.860
That's enough, Mellie.
Oh, I'm sorry.

11:35.862 --> 11:37.629
Did you not want
to go there today?

11:43.670 --> 11:46.037
This was...

11:46.039 --> 11:49.340
I will send you a check
for your time.

11:49.342 --> 11:50.308
Thanks, Liv.

11:50.310 --> 11:53.712
Thank you so much
for your help.

12:04.591 --> 12:06.057
Here he is.

12:06.059 --> 12:07.726
DAVID: Thank you, Amber.

12:07.728 --> 12:09.227
[ Door closes ]

12:09.229 --> 12:10.695
So, what's on
the agenda today?

12:10.697 --> 12:12.163
Down, boy.

12:12.165 --> 12:13.698
Really?

12:13.700 --> 12:15.300
I mean, I suppose.

12:19.239 --> 12:20.171
Get up.

12:20.173 --> 12:22.340
This is work, not play.

12:23.844 --> 12:25.543
I -- I need you
to do something for me.

12:25.545 --> 12:26.778
Okay, name it.

12:26.780 --> 12:28.780
Get Susan Ross
to run for President.

12:28.782 --> 12:30.548
Oh, that is not
going to happen.

12:30.550 --> 12:32.083
Susan Ross doesn't want
to run for President.

12:32.085 --> 12:34.119
I don't care
what<i> she</i> wants.

12:34.121 --> 12:36.755
This isn't about her.
This is about<i> me.</i>

12:36.757 --> 12:40.058
Being the Veep's Chief of Staff
is not gonna be my legacy.

12:40.060 --> 12:41.793
That woman is my shot
at the Oval.

12:41.795 --> 12:43.762
I cannot convince Susan Ross
to do something

12:43.764 --> 12:45.130
she has no intention
of doing.

12:45.132 --> 12:46.731
I think you can.

12:46.733 --> 12:49.033
I think you have
certain gifts --

12:49.035 --> 12:50.201
Okay, I gave her
that bracelet

12:50.203 --> 12:51.770
only after you said
you didn't want it,

12:51.772 --> 12:53.238
so you can't use it
against me.

12:53.240 --> 12:54.706
David, no one wants
that bracelet.

12:54.708 --> 12:55.740
That bracelet is hideous.

12:55.742 --> 12:57.242
Susan likes it.

12:57.244 --> 12:58.777
Because that Muppet
is in love with you.

12:58.779 --> 13:00.912
Use it.

13:00.914 --> 13:03.581
Ask her out.

13:03.583 --> 13:04.983
Do some convincing.

13:04.985 --> 13:07.819
Give her what she wants.

13:07.821 --> 13:09.454
Because if you don't,

13:09.456 --> 13:13.291
you won't be getting
what you want anytime soon.

13:15.595 --> 13:17.128
[ Door opens ]

13:19.132 --> 13:20.665
David!
Is this a bad time?

13:20.667 --> 13:22.734
For you, never.

13:22.736 --> 13:25.303
Please, come in.

13:25.305 --> 13:26.171
What's up?

13:26.173 --> 13:27.639
I, uh...

13:27.641 --> 13:30.675
Wanted to see if you'd like
to get out of here.

13:30.677 --> 13:31.976
I don't know what you mean.

13:31.978 --> 13:34.379
I was thinking
we could go somewhere.

13:36.283 --> 13:38.650
Again, I don't know
what you mean.

13:38.652 --> 13:41.186
Would you like to go out
with me, Susan.

13:41.188 --> 13:43.755
Oh. Oh!

13:43.757 --> 13:45.790
As in...

13:45.792 --> 13:47.192
Just the two of us?

13:47.194 --> 13:49.194
That is how a date usually
works, at least in my book.

13:49.196 --> 13:50.028
Where?!

13:50.030 --> 13:51.529
[ Chuckles ]

13:51.531 --> 13:54.666
I mean...

13:54.668 --> 13:59.504
Where are you thinking we'd go,
just the two of us.

13:59.506 --> 14:00.705
If we leave now,

14:00.707 --> 14:02.807
we can still catch the sunset
at Mount Vernon.

14:02.809 --> 14:04.776
It sure is beautiful,
isn't it?

14:04.778 --> 14:06.845
Oh, you've already been.

14:06.847 --> 14:09.314
I chartered a boat there
for Casey's 11th birthday.

14:09.316 --> 14:10.648
It really was something,

14:10.650 --> 14:12.650
seeing the sun fade
into the Potomac like that.

14:12.652 --> 14:14.052
Scratch that idea.

14:14.054 --> 14:15.687
How about a picnic
in the park?

14:15.689 --> 14:17.956
There's this great spot I know
along the Tidal Basin.

14:17.958 --> 14:19.190
That is a great idea.

14:19.192 --> 14:20.625
They shut down
the Tidal Basin

14:20.627 --> 14:22.393
when I picnicked there
with Casey just last Tuesday.

14:22.395 --> 14:24.162
It was pretty spectacular.

14:24.164 --> 14:26.130
I bet it was.

14:26.132 --> 14:28.333
I bet everything you do
is pretty spectacular.

14:28.335 --> 14:30.735
You're the Vice President
of the United States.

14:32.672 --> 14:35.139
There are all kinds of things
I haven't done.

14:35.141 --> 14:36.207
Really.

14:36.209 --> 14:37.842
Name something else.

14:37.844 --> 14:40.845
Have you been to the top
of the Washington Monument?

14:40.847 --> 14:41.913
No.

14:44.851 --> 14:46.651
Yes. I'm sorry.

14:46.653 --> 14:49.888
Ah, you can change your mind
and cancel.

14:49.890 --> 14:52.257
I get it. I ruined the vibe,
and I feel awful, so just --

14:52.259 --> 14:53.925
Susan.
Yeah?

14:53.927 --> 14:55.393
What are your feelings
on french fries?

14:56.897 --> 14:59.030
Welcome to Gettysburger.

14:59.032 --> 15:01.165
Breakfast, lunch, and dinner

15:01.167 --> 15:04.402
for the people, of the people,
and by the people.

15:04.404 --> 15:05.870
May I take your order?

15:05.872 --> 15:08.606
You have got
to be kidding me.

15:08.608 --> 15:09.741
I can't believe
you've never been here.

15:09.743 --> 15:11.175
[ Gasps ]

15:11.177 --> 15:12.577
Ooh, is the Double Lincoln
as good as it sounds?

15:12.579 --> 15:13.678
I want that.

15:13.680 --> 15:15.079
Now, that comes
with freedom fries.

15:15.081 --> 15:16.948
You're also gonna want
union rings.

15:16.950 --> 15:18.216
But I thought
I had to choose.

15:18.218 --> 15:20.251
No, union and freedom
go together.

15:20.253 --> 15:21.953
Ah.

15:25.892 --> 15:27.792
[ Door opens ]

15:27.794 --> 15:30.428
Got a minute, sir?

15:30.430 --> 15:33.097
Is this another warning
about Lillian Forrester?

15:33.099 --> 15:35.733
It's about Reagan.

15:35.735 --> 15:36.801
Reagan?

15:36.803 --> 15:37.902
Ronald.

15:37.904 --> 15:39.871
Yes, I know.

15:39.873 --> 15:41.873
It's 1988, late spring.

15:41.875 --> 15:44.642
By most accounts, he's wandering
around the residence

15:44.644 --> 15:48.546
during work hours in slippers
and a terry cloth robe.

15:48.548 --> 15:53.952
Six months left on his term,
every excuse to just sit around,

15:53.954 --> 15:57.121
watch daytime soaps,
eating ants on a log.

15:57.123 --> 15:59.457
Reagan loved ants on a log.
Did you know that?

15:59.459 --> 16:01.459
It doesn't matter.

16:01.461 --> 16:04.062
But instead,
he strapped on his cleats,

16:04.064 --> 16:06.497
tightened his chinstrap
one last time,

16:06.499 --> 16:07.899
and kicked down
the Berlin Wall.

16:07.901 --> 16:09.334
[ Chuckles ]

16:09.336 --> 16:10.902
Simplifying history a bit,
aren't you, Cy?

16:10.904 --> 16:12.403
For better or for worse,

16:12.405 --> 16:15.773
Clinton reformed welfare
in his final year.

16:15.775 --> 16:18.843
Is there a point here?

16:18.845 --> 16:21.646
You're gonna miss it.

16:21.648 --> 16:25.083
The wars. The fights.

16:25.085 --> 16:27.118
Crafting an agenda
and seeing it through,

16:27.120 --> 16:30.088
going toe-to-toe
with Senate Dems,

16:30.090 --> 16:36.494
rallying Tea Party support
for a judicial nominee.

16:36.496 --> 16:38.763
Cramming a good bill
like the Brandon Bill

16:38.765 --> 16:40.865
down the opposition's throat.

16:40.867 --> 16:43.167
Then licking your wounds,

16:43.169 --> 16:45.737
knowing you did good
for the American people.

16:47.841 --> 16:50.508
Next November...

16:50.510 --> 16:53.478
you're gonna get
an eviction notice.

16:53.480 --> 16:57.281
And by January 20th,
they're coming for your stuff.

16:57.283 --> 17:01.819
Do you know
what today's date is, sir?

17:01.821 --> 17:06.624
Not January 20th.
We can still do something.

17:06.626 --> 17:08.459
We can.

17:08.461 --> 17:10.495
Still.

17:10.497 --> 17:12.363
Set the world on fire
or die trying.

17:12.365 --> 17:15.500
Let's ride out of here
with our guns empty,

17:15.502 --> 17:17.902
not in the damn holster.

17:17.904 --> 17:21.539
This<i> is</i> about
Lillian Forrester.

17:21.541 --> 17:24.642
I can't be someone
who will take your gun away

17:24.644 --> 17:28.312
and serve you ants on a log
while you sit in your robe.

17:31.217 --> 17:33.317
Are we done?

17:43.897 --> 17:46.130
I believe so, sir.

18:09.055 --> 18:11.489
[ Tapping on door ]

18:35.281 --> 18:37.148
[ Belt buckle jangles ]

18:44.324 --> 18:48.126
[ Box springs bouncing ]

18:58.471 --> 19:00.404
I'm glad you could get past
your issues with me.

19:00.406 --> 19:01.772
[ Pants zip ]

19:01.774 --> 19:04.375
This isn't happening again.

19:05.578 --> 19:06.744
Yes, it is.

19:10.283 --> 19:12.984
[ Sighs ]
[ Door opens, closes ]

19:12.986 --> 19:17.021
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

19:17.023 --> 19:19.157
[ Indistinct conversations ]

19:21.694 --> 19:23.761
CYRUS: This is my bar.

19:23.763 --> 19:27.198
You're in my bar.

19:27.200 --> 19:30.835
This is the first bar I've been
in since college, I think.

19:30.837 --> 19:34.038
I haven't paid for a drink
in two decades.

19:38.978 --> 19:41.279
[ Sighs ]

19:41.281 --> 19:44.348
I used to come here
to feel better.

19:51.891 --> 19:54.125
I came here to be alone.

19:56.196 --> 19:58.329
[ Chuckles ]

19:58.331 --> 20:03.534
You can divorce them,
but you can't get rid of them.

20:11.678 --> 20:14.145
Fitz or Olivia?

20:17.016 --> 20:20.351
Both.

20:20.353 --> 20:24.322
We are married to them
for the rest of our lives.

20:24.324 --> 20:26.324
They are cinder blocks
tied to our ankles,

20:26.326 --> 20:29.260
and we just keep fighting
to keep from drowning,

20:29.262 --> 20:30.561
but what's the point?

20:30.563 --> 20:33.064
We're going down
whether we fight or not.

20:33.066 --> 20:35.166
I don't feel sorry for you.

20:35.168 --> 20:37.335
Surprise.

20:37.337 --> 20:39.337
You have the most recognizable
name in politics.

20:39.339 --> 20:40.938
You're a woman at a time

20:40.940 --> 20:43.674
the country is ready
for a woman president.

20:43.676 --> 20:46.377
Not to mention
that filibuster of yours

20:46.379 --> 20:48.079
is the feminist moment
of the decade.

20:48.081 --> 20:50.681
It'll be in history books.

20:50.683 --> 20:52.283
You have weaknesses, sure.

20:52.285 --> 20:55.086
But they're well-documented.

20:55.088 --> 20:57.054
Susan is an unknown.

20:57.056 --> 21:00.091
You can tear her apart
with every new --

21:00.093 --> 21:03.794
I already have my eye on someone
to run my campaign.

21:06.099 --> 21:07.565
[ Scoffs ]

21:07.567 --> 21:09.200
Right.

21:22.048 --> 21:23.381
[ Sighs ]

21:25.285 --> 21:26.350
We made him.

21:27.954 --> 21:31.389
We made
Fitzgerald Grant III.

21:33.426 --> 21:36.460
We made a president.

21:36.462 --> 21:38.029
We?

21:42.635 --> 21:44.168
We?

21:48.007 --> 21:49.473
Drink up.

22:01.087 --> 22:04.455
So, this is the love shack
where all the magic happened?

22:04.457 --> 22:06.023
Mellie, it's late.
You should -- Mm.

22:06.025 --> 22:07.658
It's nice.
You have good taste.

22:07.660 --> 22:09.627
Mellie, are you...

22:09.629 --> 22:10.861
It was working.

22:10.863 --> 22:12.163
I'm sorry?

22:12.165 --> 22:14.165
It was working.
That's why I stayed.

22:14.167 --> 22:17.034
It was working.
Fitz and I and you.

22:17.036 --> 22:19.637
It was working.
You know what I mean?

22:19.639 --> 22:21.772
I'm not sure
I do know what you --

22:21.774 --> 22:23.274
Hold on a minute.

22:26.813 --> 22:28.846
[ Sighs, laughs ]

22:28.848 --> 22:31.182
I used to wonder
if it was all men or just Fitz

22:31.184 --> 22:32.516
that suck the life
out of you.

22:32.518 --> 22:34.885
Now I think
it's all the powerful men.

22:34.887 --> 22:37.388
They've been told their whole
lives they deserve everything,

22:37.390 --> 22:43.027
they should have everything,
and it makes them so weak.

22:43.029 --> 22:45.229
They think that everything
belongs to them by default.

22:45.231 --> 22:49.967
And if they don't get it,
well, they just fall apart.

22:49.969 --> 22:51.202
Fitz didn't have
any fight in him.

22:51.204 --> 22:53.371
He didn't know how to stand
on his own two feet.

22:53.373 --> 22:56.340
I mean, I saw the potential.
We all saw it.

22:56.342 --> 22:58.342
But I had to work at it.

22:58.344 --> 23:01.912
I held his hand,
I fluffed, I bled,

23:01.914 --> 23:05.750
and I got nothing
in return.

23:05.752 --> 23:07.752
Except for you.

23:07.754 --> 23:10.755
You showed up.

23:10.757 --> 23:14.558
I wasn't devastated, Olivia,
or numb or empty.

23:14.560 --> 23:16.560
[ Sighs ]

23:16.562 --> 23:18.162
I was deserving.

23:20.500 --> 23:22.066
I deserved you.

23:23.836 --> 23:25.936
I was a 37-year-old
governor's wife

23:25.938 --> 23:29.240
with two kids,
and that was all.

23:29.242 --> 23:34.078
I was somebody's wife
and somebody's mother.

23:34.080 --> 23:36.180
Not my own anything.

23:36.182 --> 23:38.115
I deserved you.

23:38.117 --> 23:40.017
I warranted you.

23:40.019 --> 23:42.353
I justified you.

23:42.355 --> 23:48.192
I had lost myself, and
[chuckles] in return, I got you.

23:48.194 --> 23:50.995
You are my retribution.

23:52.131 --> 23:54.532
And it was humiliating.

23:56.102 --> 23:58.636
I couldn't even hate you.
I couldn't even pretend to.

23:58.638 --> 24:02.540
I hated myself.

24:02.542 --> 24:04.542
But then I turned a corner.

24:04.544 --> 24:06.043
[ Laughs ]

24:06.045 --> 24:07.912
It was quick.

24:07.914 --> 24:09.547
Effortless, really.

24:09.549 --> 24:13.083
You had become the beautiful
kept thing he lusted after.

24:13.085 --> 24:14.285
Where you went, he went.

24:14.287 --> 24:17.288
Which meant that I...

24:17.290 --> 24:20.124
I suddenly had space.

24:20.126 --> 24:23.427
I had air of my own
that I could breathe.

24:23.429 --> 24:25.830
Time to think and plan.

24:25.832 --> 24:29.233
And I started
liking myself again,

24:29.235 --> 24:32.303
because I was alone
and I was relieved

24:32.305 --> 24:34.138
and I was free.

24:36.242 --> 24:38.409
Freedom, baby.

24:38.411 --> 24:40.077
Whew.

24:45.585 --> 24:48.486
I stayed
because it was working.

24:48.488 --> 24:50.521
I stood by and I allowed
the affair to continue

24:50.523 --> 24:53.157
because it was working
for all of us.

24:53.159 --> 24:55.192
He was occupied,
thanks to you.

24:55.194 --> 24:58.262
He was happy.
You lit his fire.

24:58.264 --> 25:00.965
We made it all the way
to 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue.

25:00.967 --> 25:04.468
And one day,
it was gonna be my turn.

25:04.470 --> 25:06.203
Fitz would make me
President of the United States,

25:06.205 --> 25:10.708
because he owed me
at least that much.

25:10.710 --> 25:14.144
And so I stayed.

25:14.146 --> 25:18.015
Because the three of us,
ugh.

25:18.017 --> 25:20.551
We worked!

25:20.553 --> 25:23.821
[ Sighs ]

25:23.823 --> 25:25.122
So, what do you say,
Olivia?

25:25.124 --> 25:27.725
That deep enough for you?

25:27.727 --> 25:31.795
Is that honest enough?

25:33.833 --> 25:37.868
Mellie, you can't actually
write that anywhere.

25:37.870 --> 25:39.236
If you want to be President,

25:39.238 --> 25:42.373
you can never, ever tell anyone
any of that.

25:42.375 --> 25:45.309
Oh, yeah, I know.

25:45.311 --> 25:49.380
I know I can't.

25:49.382 --> 25:52.316
That's the problem.

25:56.989 --> 26:00.090
♪♪

26:20.413 --> 26:23.013
[ Clears throat ]

26:23.015 --> 26:24.515
Hm.

26:26.686 --> 26:27.918
[ Sighs ]

26:33.559 --> 26:35.559
That was...

26:35.561 --> 26:38.128
incredible.

26:38.130 --> 26:40.464
What do you think their
secret sauce is made out of?

26:40.466 --> 26:42.232
Crack.

26:42.234 --> 26:43.968
I think it's made
out of crack.

26:43.970 --> 26:46.303
[ Chuckles ]

26:46.305 --> 26:47.371
[ Laughs ]

26:47.373 --> 26:50.140
What?

26:50.142 --> 26:51.775
We shut down
a Gettysburger.

26:51.777 --> 26:53.143
A Gettysburger.

26:53.145 --> 26:54.244
That's power.

26:54.246 --> 26:56.280
It's obnoxious.

26:56.282 --> 26:58.248
Making these kids stay late,

26:58.250 --> 27:00.250
inconveniencing
all these people,

27:00.252 --> 27:03.053
denying the neighborhood
of Fourscores.

27:03.055 --> 27:04.755
Can you imagine the story
that would be written

27:04.757 --> 27:06.123
if the press got ahold
of this?

27:06.125 --> 27:09.159
Actually, I imagine that would
be a pretty great story.

27:09.161 --> 27:13.230
Susan's just a regular American,
very "woman of the people."

27:13.232 --> 27:15.232
That kind of story
makes people think of you

27:15.234 --> 27:17.234
as Grade-A
presidential material.

27:20.006 --> 27:21.305
Now you're sounding like Liz.

27:22.408 --> 27:24.408
Liz?

27:24.410 --> 27:27.811
No matter how many times I tell
her "no," or "stop,"

27:27.813 --> 27:30.848
or "I don't want to form
an exploratory committee,"

27:30.850 --> 27:31.849
she doesn't let up.

27:31.851 --> 27:33.784
She wants you to make a run?

27:33.786 --> 27:34.985
I didn't know.

27:34.987 --> 27:36.286
Well, I agree with her.

27:36.288 --> 27:40.924
You would be
an amazing president.

27:40.926 --> 27:44.294
David...

27:44.296 --> 27:47.765
Do you know why
I was chosen to be VP?

27:47.767 --> 27:50.167
It wasn't because
I am amazing.

27:50.169 --> 27:54.471
It's because
Mellie Grant lacks character.

27:54.473 --> 27:58.142
She was picking her competition
for the next Republican primary.

27:58.144 --> 28:00.844
And instead of having the guts
to go toe-to-toe

28:00.846 --> 28:05.282
with a worthy warrior for a
true battle, she turned coward.

28:05.284 --> 28:07.151
She picked me.

28:07.153 --> 28:10.554
She picked someone useless,
unthreatening,

28:10.556 --> 28:13.457
unpolished, unelectable.

28:13.459 --> 28:17.327
She picked a bug
she can crush in one blow.

28:17.329 --> 28:20.297
I don't stand a chance
in a primary against Mellie,

28:20.299 --> 28:23.734
so why would I put myself,
my daughter,

28:23.736 --> 28:25.469
through the agony
of a campaign?

28:25.471 --> 28:27.905
Why would I uproot us
for months on end...

28:34.847 --> 28:38.315
Don't you ever call yourself
names in my presence again.

28:38.317 --> 28:40.184
You are not a bug.

28:40.186 --> 28:41.919
You are a warrior.

28:41.921 --> 28:44.254
You could win this.

28:44.256 --> 28:45.556
You could win, Susan.

28:45.558 --> 28:47.324
I really believe that.

28:54.934 --> 28:56.600
[ Laughs ]

28:56.602 --> 28:59.937
You were mean.

28:59.939 --> 29:01.638
Of course I was.

29:01.640 --> 29:02.940
You were
my husband's mistress.

29:02.942 --> 29:04.174
Was I supposed to be
friendly?

29:05.678 --> 29:07.277
You were really awful.

29:07.279 --> 29:10.247
I'm telling you,
you were nasty.

29:10.249 --> 29:11.782
And I took it.

29:11.784 --> 29:14.251
Why? I wanted to fight.
You never fought.

29:14.253 --> 29:18.288
I was
your husband's mistress.

29:18.290 --> 29:19.890
I was in the wrong.

29:19.892 --> 29:23.293
[ Sighs ]

29:23.295 --> 29:26.196
Truth is,
I was glad you were there.

29:26.198 --> 29:27.898
You were a good mistress.

29:27.900 --> 29:29.533
Probably a great one.

29:29.535 --> 29:31.568
[ Sighs ]

29:31.570 --> 29:34.404
You know what I mean?

29:34.406 --> 29:35.205
Mm.

29:35.207 --> 29:38.442
Well,
I am an overachiever.

29:38.444 --> 29:42.446
Once I put my mind
to something, I commit.

29:49.955 --> 29:51.822
[ Both laugh ]

29:59.799 --> 30:01.098
Ohh.

30:01.100 --> 30:02.800
Tell me you brought more.

30:02.802 --> 30:05.169
Oh, damn straight I did.

30:05.171 --> 30:06.670
[ Grunts ]

30:06.672 --> 30:08.539
[ Giggles ]

30:13.646 --> 30:17.481
I was happy
you were around, too.

30:17.483 --> 30:20.484
[ Sighs ]

30:24.957 --> 30:31.762
When I was with Fitz, I was
happy you were around, too.

30:31.764 --> 30:35.199
With you around,
I didn't have to...

30:43.943 --> 30:46.543
I had an out.

30:46.545 --> 30:50.447
You --
you were my out, Mellie.

30:50.449 --> 30:54.418
You kept him unavailable.

30:58.891 --> 31:02.226
Okay.

31:02.228 --> 31:03.627
[ Voice breaking ]
And...

31:03.629 --> 31:05.729
So...

31:09.401 --> 31:14.071
I left for the same reason
you stayed.

31:19.011 --> 31:21.645
Because I was scared.

31:24.884 --> 31:26.717
[ Voice breaking ]
Okay.

31:31.657 --> 31:35.425
Mellie.

31:35.427 --> 31:37.628
That's what you write.

31:38.931 --> 31:42.499
You write
that you were scared.

31:42.501 --> 31:45.903
You write that you never
could have imagined

31:45.905 --> 31:48.272
standing up in front
of the entire Senate

31:48.274 --> 31:49.773
for as long as you did,

31:49.775 --> 31:52.175
filibustering the hell
out of that bill,

31:52.177 --> 31:54.678
protecting every woman's
constitutional right

31:54.680 --> 31:57.114
to make her own decision
about her own body

31:57.116 --> 31:59.616
because you never thought

31:59.618 --> 32:02.119
you would be able to do
any of that on your own.

32:02.121 --> 32:05.222
You write that
you didn't need Fitz --

32:05.224 --> 32:08.859
you didn't need some man
to give you the power.

32:08.861 --> 32:12.029
You had the power
the whole time.

32:12.031 --> 32:15.399
It just took you
a little longer to realize.

32:15.401 --> 32:18.368
That is what you write.
[ Glass clinks ]

32:22.207 --> 32:24.007
Get out your laptop.
Start writing.

32:25.577 --> 32:27.878
Uh...

32:35.721 --> 32:38.789
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

32:52.271 --> 32:53.370
Sir.

32:57.009 --> 32:59.176
Mr. President.

32:59.178 --> 33:00.477
What's wrong?

33:00.479 --> 33:01.812
It's my cousin, sir.

33:01.814 --> 33:03.647
He died an hour ago.

33:03.649 --> 33:05.182
Cyrus.

33:05.184 --> 33:07.284
I have to go.

33:07.286 --> 33:08.318
I'm so sorry.

33:09.588 --> 33:11.254
Me, too.

33:30.142 --> 33:34.444
Okay, um, I'll just start with
the general, Mr. President.

33:34.446 --> 33:36.546
Mm-hmm.

33:36.548 --> 33:40.183
Is the country better off today
than it was seven years ago

33:40.185 --> 33:42.619
when a young governor
from California

33:42.621 --> 33:45.655
waltzed into this very room
and vowed to work tirelessly

33:45.657 --> 33:46.890
for his people?

33:46.892 --> 33:49.359
Well, first,
thanks for calling me young.

33:49.361 --> 33:50.627
And second, absolutely.

33:50.629 --> 33:52.229
Unemployment's down.
The economy's up.

33:52.231 --> 33:53.397
I think the world
in general is --

33:53.399 --> 33:55.032
[ Recorder beeps ]

33:55.034 --> 33:57.667
I'm sorry.

33:57.669 --> 33:58.835
Something I said.

33:58.837 --> 34:01.972
I don't know.
I wasn't listening.

34:01.974 --> 34:05.042
I'm a respected journalist.
I have a Pulitzer.

34:05.044 --> 34:08.512
I spent a week with Putin,
and yet I cannot focus.

34:08.514 --> 34:11.181
Well, I know all this
can be overwhelming.

34:11.183 --> 34:13.417
I have an enormous crush
on you.

34:17.423 --> 34:18.688
Wow.

34:18.690 --> 34:21.224
This really couldn't be
any more awkward.

34:21.226 --> 34:23.693
This is a clear conflict
of interest.

34:23.695 --> 34:25.062
I know.
I'm so sorry.

34:25.064 --> 34:27.697
Not just on your account,
Lillian.

34:27.699 --> 34:30.534
How about...

34:30.536 --> 34:34.704
We nix this whole interview
and instead...

34:34.706 --> 34:36.406
you have dinner with me?

34:40.179 --> 34:41.344
Sir, are you asking me out
on a date?

34:41.346 --> 34:43.780
I am.

34:43.782 --> 34:47.517
But only if you stop
calling me "sir."

34:47.519 --> 34:49.853
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

34:49.855 --> 34:52.789
Ordinarily,
I don't come when called.

34:52.791 --> 34:54.391
But...
Glad you did.

34:54.393 --> 34:56.093
Game's over. I'm out.

34:56.095 --> 34:57.294
David --
No.

34:57.296 --> 34:59.062
Susan Ross is a good person.

34:59.064 --> 35:01.031
She's smart
and compassionate

35:01.033 --> 35:03.366
and has the best interests
of the country at heart.

35:03.368 --> 35:05.202
People like that
don't exist in this town.

35:05.204 --> 35:06.770
She's a political unicorn.

35:06.772 --> 35:08.138
And if she doesn't want
to run for President,

35:08.140 --> 35:09.439
she shouldn't have to.

35:09.441 --> 35:10.474
Is that so?

35:10.476 --> 35:11.775
I won't manipulate her.

35:11.777 --> 35:13.577
And you won't manipulate me.

35:13.579 --> 35:15.345
I'm done buying
what you're selling.

35:17.082 --> 35:19.116
She filed the paperwork.

35:19.118 --> 35:20.317
She's running.

35:20.319 --> 35:24.054
You did good, Rosen.

35:24.056 --> 35:25.989
Whatever you said to her,
it worked.

35:25.991 --> 35:27.657
She doesn't want this.

35:27.659 --> 35:30.327
Well, Little Bo Veep
doesn't know what she wants.

35:31.897 --> 35:34.898
Lucky for her,
she has us.

35:39.404 --> 35:41.438
Come on, Rosen.

35:41.440 --> 35:44.141
Let's make a president
together.

35:47.779 --> 35:50.013
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

35:55.287 --> 35:57.487
I already e-mailed you
my corrections, Marcus.

35:57.489 --> 35:59.022
I just got 'em.

35:59.024 --> 36:01.424
I'm not going anywhere,
Huck.

36:11.336 --> 36:12.702
Nice picture quality.

36:12.704 --> 36:15.038
QR18?

36:15.040 --> 36:16.506
19.

36:16.508 --> 36:19.109
I remotely inserted the
program's facial filament

36:19.111 --> 36:20.777
into a couple
of traffic cams.

36:20.779 --> 36:23.713
It's like you're right there.
Whoa, who's that? He's a beast.

36:23.715 --> 36:27.317
That's my son, Javi.

36:27.319 --> 36:29.319
Your son?

36:29.321 --> 36:30.387
Skills.

36:30.389 --> 36:31.855
You teach him
how to dribble like that?

36:31.857 --> 36:34.057
I wish.

36:34.059 --> 36:36.660
How often do you catch
his games?

36:36.662 --> 36:39.062
I've never been
to one of his games.

36:40.799 --> 36:42.065
Divorce?

36:42.067 --> 36:45.368
Something like that.

36:45.370 --> 36:48.305
That sucks, man.

36:48.307 --> 36:49.906
I'm sorry.

36:49.908 --> 36:53.510
They moved...recently.

36:53.512 --> 36:56.046
They moved.

36:56.048 --> 36:57.747
So I haven't seen him.

36:57.749 --> 37:00.884
You should.

37:00.886 --> 37:02.185
You should go see him.

37:02.187 --> 37:05.155
I bet Javi
would love that.

37:19.271 --> 37:20.370
Hm.

37:20.372 --> 37:22.172
This is good.

37:22.174 --> 37:25.041
This is really good.

37:25.043 --> 37:27.143
You think so?
I<i> know</i> so.

37:29.615 --> 37:32.716
Hm. This...

37:32.718 --> 37:35.552
is everything.

37:35.554 --> 37:39.222
Thanks.

37:39.224 --> 37:40.690
Read this part.

37:40.692 --> 37:43.093
[ Chuckles ]

37:44.763 --> 37:46.630
You know it won't
do you any good

37:46.632 --> 37:48.265
if this book comes out
in a couple of months, right?

37:48.267 --> 37:49.299
It won't?

37:49.301 --> 37:50.867
Other people will be
announcing sooner.

37:50.869 --> 37:53.536
If you wait even a month, you're
gonna be late to the party.

37:53.538 --> 37:55.705
It has to come out now.
That's impossible.

37:55.707 --> 37:57.207
The publisher says
it will take at least six weeks

37:57.209 --> 37:58.108
to get it into bookstores --

37:58.110 --> 37:59.476
Who says
we need bookstores?

38:02.581 --> 38:05.448
Several pages of the former
First Lady's upcoming memoir

38:05.450 --> 38:07.117
appear today
on the D.C. Dish's website.

38:07.119 --> 38:08.618
Both the publisher
and Senator Grant herself

38:08.620 --> 38:10.387
denied being the source
of the leak.

38:10.389 --> 38:12.289
The book, however,
is being described

38:12.291 --> 38:14.758
by those who have read it
as explosive, revealing,

38:14.760 --> 38:15.558
and deeply personal.

38:15.560 --> 38:16.826
"And during that filibuster,

38:16.828 --> 38:19.396
I found that I could stand
as long as I needed.

38:19.398 --> 38:23.633
Hours, days,
whatever the Senate required.

38:23.635 --> 38:25.602
Because for the first time
in my adult life,

38:25.604 --> 38:27.637
I was no longer an accessory,

38:27.639 --> 38:30.340
an appendage to the most
powerful man in the world.

38:30.342 --> 38:33.310
That's when I discovered
that I, too, was strong,

38:33.312 --> 38:36.079
that I, too, was powerful,

38:36.081 --> 38:39.082
that he hadn't taken everything
from me,

38:39.084 --> 38:41.351
that I could stand
on my own."

38:44.756 --> 38:46.489
There you have it.

38:46.491 --> 38:48.458
Powerful words
from what will certainly be

38:48.460 --> 38:52.195
a forceful candidate
in the form of Mellie Grant.

38:52.197 --> 38:55.265
Watch your back,
Vice President Ross.

38:55.267 --> 38:57.634
Oh, Marianne,
I'm just testing the waters.

38:57.636 --> 38:59.202
It's like
when you like someone.

38:59.204 --> 39:01.338
You want to see
if they like you back.

39:01.340 --> 39:05.608
I like America, and now
I'm hoping America will call me.

39:07.112 --> 39:08.678
So that's who
our Republican brethren

39:08.680 --> 39:11.214
can look forward to roasting
on the spit.

39:11.216 --> 39:13.283
But what of the Democrats?

39:13.285 --> 39:15.652
What lambs will they serve up
for the slaughter?

39:15.654 --> 39:17.120
ABBY:
He's going on a date.

39:17.122 --> 39:19.289
This is "50 Shades of Wrong"
here, Cyrus.

39:19.291 --> 39:20.690
I need you.

39:20.692 --> 39:21.991
Oh, crap.

39:21.993 --> 39:23.526
You're at your cousin's funeral
right now, aren't you?

39:23.528 --> 39:24.994
Ah, yes.

39:24.996 --> 39:27.130
Oh, I totally forgot.
I'm so sorry.

39:27.132 --> 39:28.798
It's okay.
We weren't close.

39:28.800 --> 39:30.133
Still, he's dead.

39:30.135 --> 39:31.835
Well, it's for the best.

39:31.837 --> 39:33.703
Well,
can you talk to him?

39:33.705 --> 39:34.537
My dead cousin?

39:34.539 --> 39:36.005
The President!

39:36.007 --> 39:37.374
I'm out of my league here.

39:37.376 --> 39:38.575
No can do.

39:38.577 --> 39:41.411
I told you, Red,
you're the work wife, not me.

39:41.413 --> 39:43.713
This is not what being
a work wife means.

39:43.715 --> 39:45.315
[ Sighs ]
Wake's starting.

39:45.317 --> 39:46.383
I got to go.

39:46.385 --> 39:48.752
Very sad.

39:48.754 --> 39:52.355
WOMAN: I've paid my taxes
in this county for 19 years.

39:52.357 --> 39:54.491
I understand your concerns,
your issues.

39:54.493 --> 39:55.825
That is why I'm here.

39:55.827 --> 39:58.528
It's why I'm visiting every
county in the state

39:58.530 --> 39:59.763
to discuss the particulars --

39:59.765 --> 40:01.331
I don't see why
my tax dollars

40:01.333 --> 40:03.199
are helping other people
go to college.

40:03.201 --> 40:04.868
I didn't even go
to college.

40:04.870 --> 40:07.437
[ Indistinct talking ]
I'm sorry you didn't have
that opportunity.

40:07.439 --> 40:09.205
Under my plan,
you would have --

40:09.207 --> 40:10.340
WAYNE: What don't you get,
Governor?

40:10.342 --> 40:12.609
We don't want
your stinking education bill.

40:12.611 --> 40:15.945
[ Cheers and applause ]

40:15.947 --> 40:18.281
I know that this is personal
for many of you.

40:18.283 --> 40:19.849
It is personal for me, too.

40:19.851 --> 40:23.186
My parents had very little
education growing up in Mexico,

40:23.188 --> 40:26.356
and there was no chance of them
going to college -- none.

40:26.358 --> 40:29.559
And then they came here,
to America, to Pennsylvania.

40:29.561 --> 40:31.394
My mother went
to nursing school.

40:31.396 --> 40:33.196
My father,
who came from nothing,

40:33.198 --> 40:35.732
earned his PhD
at Penn State,

40:35.734 --> 40:39.803
and their two sons had access to
the best public education system

40:39.805 --> 40:42.038
in the greatest country
on Earth.

40:42.040 --> 40:44.140
[ Scattered applause ]

40:44.142 --> 40:48.411
A college degree
is as essential today

40:48.413 --> 40:51.781
as a high-school diploma was
100 years ago.

40:51.783 --> 40:55.485
The world is changing, and
we have got to change with it.

40:55.487 --> 40:58.321
That means that our state
colleges and universities

40:58.323 --> 41:01.658
should be free for
every high-school graduate.

41:01.660 --> 41:04.194
[ Cheers and applause ]

41:06.898 --> 41:12.602
My education bill -- it's
not revolutionary or radical.

41:12.604 --> 41:16.639
It simply finishes
what we've been working on

41:16.641 --> 41:19.509
in this great state
for over 300 years --

41:19.511 --> 41:22.278
the principle of free education
was established

41:22.280 --> 41:25.081
in the Pennsylvania constitution
of 1790,

41:25.083 --> 41:26.850
and in the 1830s,

41:26.852 --> 41:29.319
we were one of the first states
in the country

41:29.321 --> 41:32.689
to actually establish
a public-education system.

41:32.691 --> 41:36.192
Now, that's the Pennsylvania
my parents moved to.

41:36.194 --> 41:38.595
That's the Pennsylvania
I grew up in.

41:38.597 --> 41:41.164
That is your Pennsylvania.

41:41.166 --> 41:42.599
[ Applause ]

41:42.601 --> 41:46.169
Smart, generous,

41:46.171 --> 41:49.806
civic-minded,
forward-thinking...

41:49.808 --> 41:50.840
right.

41:50.842 --> 41:53.676
[ Applause ]

41:57.015 --> 41:58.014
Sir.

41:58.016 --> 41:59.883
We can still.

41:59.885 --> 42:01.618
Set the world on fire
or die trying.

42:01.620 --> 42:02.685
We're done.

42:04.289 --> 42:05.321
Betrayal's still there.

42:05.323 --> 42:07.390
Well, he forgave you.

42:07.392 --> 42:08.892
You're fired.

42:08.894 --> 42:10.026
I have to go.

42:10.028 --> 42:10.927
I'm so sorry.

42:12.163 --> 42:13.062
Me, too.

42:13.965 --> 42:16.199
[ Cheers and applause ]
Thank you.

42:16.201 --> 42:17.300
Thank you.

42:17.302 --> 42:19.969
Thank you. Thank you.

42:19.971 --> 42:22.906
[ Cheers and applause continue ]

42:22.908 --> 42:25.875
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

42:29.080 --> 42:31.147
♪♪
